entry.title: Fix the case of negative-sized scroll_snapport_rect
entry.content:
When the scrollPadding of a scroll container is greater than its size, for

example, if the container has a height of 50px and the scrollPadding is 30px,

the scroll_snapport_rect of this container have a negative height value.

This can lead to unexpected scrolling of the container when scrollIntoView is

called on a child element within the view, ust like the example given in the

bug report.



Therefore, when the size of scroll_snapport_rect is negative, it is necessary

to set it to the minimum non-negative value.

entry.title: [//gpu] Add ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTargetForOverlays()
entry.content:
This function returns GL_TEXTURE_2D for platforms other than Mac and

the platform-specific texture target for Mac. It will be used to convert

clients that have the following pattern:



texture_target = GL_TEXTURE_2D;

texture_target = gpu::GetPlatformSpecificTextureTarget();



The existing functions *should be* sufficient for doing this exchange,

but it is challenging to reason in an iron-clad way about correctness

entry.title: view-transition: Ensure resources are cleaned up in all cases.
entry.content:
This change ensures textures generated for a ViewTransition are released

for cases where the transition is aborted before the new Document takes

ownership:



1. If the old Document's renderer crashes after generating the textures

but before the browser is notified that the snapshot operation is

complete. For this, the navigation ID is now created in the browser.



2. If the navigation is cancelled after the browser has been notified

but before the navigation commits. This is done by storing a scoped

object on the NavigationRequest.



3. If the new Document's renderer process terminates before taking

ownership of the resources. This is done by passing a scoped object

managing the resources to the new RWHV after DidCommit. Since the

RWHV lifetime is tied to the renderer process.

entry.title: Add privacy_math_perftest.cc
entry.content:
Neither counting nor sampling from the output state for event-level

randomized response is trivial, computationally. This CL adds a perf

test to see how much this costs for a few different cases:

1. Default event sources (3 states)

2. Default navigation sources (2925 states)

3. Maximal sources with 8 trigger types (4e15 states)

4. Maximal sources with 32 trigger types (1.8e26 states)



For sampling, randomized response is invoked directly which does

mean the test is non-deterministic. This was chosen intentionally to

avoid making a decision about which sequence index to choose.



The results of the perftest should help us make decisions about e.g.

the TODO about whether we should keep the "single spec" optimization:

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/attribution_reporting/privacy_math.cc;drc=2b956983e642c01dad426bf9cbdabf9f423fb693;l=521

entry.title: Implement an empty card unmask authentication coordinator.
entry.content:
When a payment card needs to be authenticated for autofilling the card

unmasking prompt needs to be shown. This change triggers a new empty

coordinator via the browser coordinator.

authentication selection that can retrieve the

controller from AutofillBottomSheetTabHelper.

CardUnmaskAuthenticationSelectionDialogControllerImpl from

entry.title: [//gpu] Destroy known WebGPU devices in WebGPUDecoderImpl destruction
entry.content:
We want to have WebGPUDecoderImpl destroy any created WebGPU devices

when it is destroyed. This will allow device destruction to propagate

throughout the system. Concrete motivation is that an upcoming change is

to going to have IOSurfaceImageBacking hold a ref to the device(s) via

SharedTextureMemory. With that change we will have IOSurfaceImageBacking

check when it should drop SharedTextureMemory instances due to the

corresponding device being lost. However, if WebGPUDecoderImpl doesn't

destroy its created devices when it goes away, then those devices will

never *be* lost as long as the IOSurfaceImageBacking is alive. This

could be problematic in the case where IOSurfaceImageBacking(s) are used

in a pool.

entry.title: [ios] Avoid LegacyBookmarkModel::root_node() to iterate all bookmarks
entry.content:
Behavioral changes only behind disabled feature flag.



This patch is part of a larger series to remove all callers for

LegacyBookmarkModel::root_node(), which doesn't have clear semantics

during the transition phase while feature

`syncer::kEnableBookmarkFoldersForAccountStorage` is rolling out.



For cases where the root is used to iterate all its children, the only

solution inherent to the LegacyBookmarkModel abstraction is to list all

permanent folders explicitly on the caller's side. Subtly enough, this

may include the managed node, which is now exposed as a new getter in

LegacyBookmarkModel.



This allows LegacyBookmarkModelWithSharedUnderlyingModel to offer

equivalent behavior, without accidentally leaking all 6 (or 7) permanent

folders, when the actual intention is to only expose a subset.



One special case is bookmark_utils_ios::DeleteBookmarks(), which is

cleaner to implement by extending LegacyBookmarkModel with a dedicated

API.

entry.title: Skip processing DispatchLoad calls on commit-intercepted RFHs
entry.content:
In tests, we can intercept DidCommit navigation callbacks to keep the

navigation in a "pending commit" stage. If this happens on a new RFH,

the RFH will also stay in the kPendingCommit state. However, since

the renderer thought it already sent the DidCommit IPC and the RFH

is now active, we might receive some IPCs that should only be called

on active RFHs, e.g. DispatchLoad, causing failed DCHECKs.



In this CL, we keep track of whether we've intercepted a commit on

a RFH before, and skip processing DispatchLoad in that case. This

shouldn't have any effect outside of tests.

entry.title: [//media] Enable 2c pure-SW VideoFrame->GL upload w/Metal, non-OOP-C
entry.content:
This CL enables 2-copy upload of pure software VideoFrames to GL when

ANGLE-Metal and non-OOP-C are being used. The thing that we need to do

in this case is create the intermediate SharedImage that holds the YUV

data of the VideoFrame via GLTextureImageBacking rather than

IOSurfaceImageBacking, as the latter doesn't support I420 as a format.



GLTextureImageBackingFactory rejects creation of

SharedImages with GLES2 usage when ANGLE-Metal is being used, as those

could be used on a different GPU than raster. However, in this case

the GLES2 usage is present *only* because we know that raster is going

over the GLES2 interface - the intermediate SI is not actually accessed

by WebGL, as it is first copied to an RGBA SI that itself is then copied

to a GL texture via WebGL's GLES2 interface. GLTextureImageBacking will

allow creation of SharedImages if it knows that the SI is in this case

via the client specifying SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_FOR_RASTER_ONLY.



For Graphite, we have an additional issue wherein we disallow

GLTextureImageBacking creation for SIs with raster usage, since raster

might not be using GL. However, in this case we *know* that raster is

going over the GLES2 interface, and thus it is fine to use

GLTextureImageBacking. GLTexture similarly will allow creation of

SharedImages in this case via the client specifying the

RASTER_OVER_GLES2_ONLY flag.



This CL adds both usages to the intermediate SI, as well as unittests

of GLTextureImageBackingFactory that specifically test that it allows

creation of SharedImages matching the parameters given for that

intermediate SI.



I have verified that this CL fixes the Google Earth crash from [1] with

Ganesh and Graphite.



I will also be developing a regression test of the high-level use case

here (import of pure-SW video frames to WebGL).



[1] https://issues.chromium.org/u/1/issues/328302269
